# *Limit Definition of a Derivative*

- Suppose we wanted to measure a runner’s instantaneous speed using a stopwatch. By instantaneous speed, we mean their speed at an exact moment in time.
- Let’s define *f(t)* as the runner’s distance from the start time at time *t*. How could we find the runner’s instantaneous speed at 1 second after the race? We could record their positions at 1 second and sometime second measurement. Then the second time is *x+h*, and the positions at the two times are *f(x)* and *f(x+h)*.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/c341a9a9-e8de-4533-85e4-b0aca7e5c776/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/2886226a-6b67-45fa-9949-e1dffe3d285e/Untitled.png)

> This is called the *derivative at a point*, which is the function’s slope (rate of change) at a specific point.
> 

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/3672fca1-a5f9-4646-9c7c-3f7579f82de7/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/0c7c7acd-4363-4edc-8e92-064b5a156811/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/a36d376f-1a70-4586-acce-aa9b8d8c44c9/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/bff4a6e2-ea6b-4ba8-ad4b-3c254a7d6bdc/Untitled.png)

