# *Calculating Derivatives*

- We can think that derivatives are *linear operators*, fancy language that means:

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/e6527334-52df-4076-b716-7e9934edb9dd/Untitled.png)

- This means that we can pull constants out when calculating a derivative. For example, say we have the following function:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/48c7ad86-638b-4e2c-aebe-fe9d4630afd0/Untitled.png)
    
- We can define the derivative as the following:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/2fc39466-061f-43f8-8b0f-08620812ca79/Untitled.png)
    

> Breaking it down further:
> 
> - (d/dx)4x^2 means we are taking the derivative of 4x^2 with respect to x.
> - Applying the **power rule** of derivatives, we multiply the coefficient (4) by the exponent (2) and reduce the exponent by 1, resulting in 8x.
> - Therefore, (d/dx)4x^2 = 8x.
- We can also say that:

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/069d6e41-02e7-4067-9dcb-c842f30e28b7/Untitled.png)

> **This means that the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives.**
> 
- For example, say we have the following function:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/829ec60d-2fc7-4bb3-8b2d-7b56c92b9458/Untitled.png)
    
- We can define the derivative as the following:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/ecf270fa-a3e4-4fd8-a4f4-818201149f71/Untitled.png)
    

> **When products get involved, derivatives can get a bit more complicated.**
> 
- For example, let’s say we have a function in the following form of two separate “parts”:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/55cd2598-e6e6-4afb-ae19-090656b6ce51/Untitled.png)
    
- We define the *product rule* as:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/ea8c8e5b-79cb-4152-87bd-fe20199936f2/Untitled.png)
    

<aside>
💡 Mnemonically, we remember this as “**first times derivative of second plus second times derivative of first”**.

</aside>

- For example:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/b6fbc783-3ffc-4ddf-a22c-002f2fbdaeeb/Untitled.png)
    
- We would use the product rule as:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/30eb0ba3-ff82-489b-9816-6ffea90866d5/Untitled.png)
    

> **Finally, one last rule to take with us into the next exercise is that the derivative of a constant is equal to 0.**
> 

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/bb98cf91-598f-42c4-ba3a-2352b48a2574/Untitled.png)

- This is because for a constant there is never any change in value, so the derivative will always equal zero. For example, we can say:

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/61c1cfc6-b9d8-44c6-a223-02b43b168170/Untitled.png)

